1. e4 {Stohl,I Schlosser,P King Stohl Stohl Schlosser,P King} d6 2. d4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. Be2 Nc6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 O-O {-B08}) (4... c5 5. dxc5 Qa5+ 6. Bd2 Qxc5 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 10. Na4 Qh5 11. Ng5 Bg4 $10 {Kimende,R-Gallego,R/Moscow olm/1994/ Kimende,R-Gallego,R/Moscow olm/1994/ Stohl: '='}) (4... a6 5. O-O Nf6 6. Nc3 b5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. exd6 cxd6 9. a4 b4 10. Nd5 Nc6 11. Bg5 Rb8 12. Re1 h6 $13 13. Bxe7 $2 Nxe7 14. Bc4 Bf6 15. Qe2 Kf8 16. Nf4 Kg7 17. Bxf7 Kxf7 18. Qe6+ Kg7 19. Qxd6 Kh7 $19 {Haimovich,T-Varga,Zo/Ramat-Hasharon/1992/}) 5. O-O (5. d5 $5 Nb8 6. c4 Nd7 7. O-O Nc5 8. Nfd2 Nf6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. f3 c6 11. Nb3 Nxb3 12. Qxb3 Nd7 13. Be3 c5 14. Qd1 a6 15. Qd2 Qa5 16. Bh6 Rb8 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Anguix Garrido,J-Brito,A/Las Palmas-B/1993/} 18. a4 $36 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6] ׻}) 5... Bg4 6. c3 (6. d5 Nb8 (6... Ne5 7. Nxe5 Bxe2 8. Qxe2 Bxe5 9. Qb5+ $16) (6... Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Ne5 (7... Nd4 $2 8. Bg4 { a4, c3 x d4 +-}) 8. Be2 $16) 7. Nc3 (7. c4 $16 {Schlosser,P}) 7... Nf6 8. Be3 O-O 9. Qd2 Re8 10. h3 Bc8 11. Rfe1 c6 12. Nd4 e5 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. Bh6 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Nbd7 16. Nf3 b5 17. e5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Bf3 Nd5 20. Rxe5 Qf6 21. Rae1 Bd7 22. h4 $14 {Nadyrhanov,S-Kochetkov,G/Alushta1/1994/}) 6... e5 $5 7. Qb3 $6 $146 (7. Be3 {Stohl: 'Schlosser,P'} Nf6 (7... exd4 $5 8. cxd4 Nge7 9. Nc3 d5 10. e5 f6 $132) 8. d5 Ne7 9. Nfd2 Bd7 10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3 Ne8 12. c5 f5 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. f3 f4 15. Bf2 g5 16. a4 h5 17. Nc4 Rf6 18. Qb3 Bc8 19. Nxe5 Rh6 20. Nc4 Ng6 21. Nb5 a6 22. Nd4 Bxd4 23. Bxd4 g4 24. Nb6 $18 {Almeyda,J-Benítez,L/Mendoza u-26 tt/1985/}) (7. d5 Nce7 8. c4 Bd7 $5 {[%cal Yf7f5] f5}) (7. Be3 {Schlosser,P}) 7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 exd4 $1 9. Qxb7 Nge7 10. e5 O-O $1 11. Bxc6 (11. exd6 Qxd6 $32 $15 {Stohl: ''}) (11. cxd4 $6 Rb8 {[%cal Rc6d4] d4}) (11. Bg5 Rb8 12. Qxc6 (12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Qxa7 dxe5 $36) 12... Nxc6 13. Bxd8 Nxd8 14. cxd4 dxe5 $15) 11... Rb8 12. Qa6 Rb6 13. Qa4 $6 {ףa4 White's strongest piece will be misplaced here.} (13. Qe2 $5 Nxc6 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Rd1 Qf6 16. Nd2 $132) 13... Nxc6 14. cxd4 Qh4 $36 15. Nc3 Nxd4 16. exd6 {King: Black could simply play 16...Rxd6 here, and it is hard to believe that he stands worse with such active pieces, even if White captured on a7. But Ashley's attention must have been drawn to the tempting 16...Ne2+ 17 Kh1 Rb4, hoping for 18 Qxa7? Qxh2+ 19 Kxh2 Rh4 mate. Unfortunately White more than saves the day with 18 Qd7, preventing the sacrifice, and leaving Black in trouble. Nevertheless, this motif must have sparked off a new line of thought, and after forty minutes Black played} {Neil McDonald: 'After'} g5 $1 {Neil McDonald: '. Exercise 2: -- Rather than recapture the pawn on d6, Black has just played the odd-looking move 16...g5. What is its purpose and why can't White play 17 dxc7 grabbing another pawn?' Neil McDonald: ', the inventive Maurice Ashley was ready to answer' King: After this, Black's position just clicks. The main point of the move is seen in the following variation: 17 dxc7 Ne2+ 18 Kh1 Qxh2+ 19 Kxh2 Rh6+. A pleasing echo of the variation above. The advance of the g-pawn allows the rook to swing over to h6, and at the same time blocks the path of the bishop from c1; moreover, it can be used to force open lines if White plays h3.  Incidentally, I showed this position to Bob Wade (without revealing 16...g5) and he came up with another idea: 16...Rb5!?, threatening Ne2+ and Qxh2+; the same mating pattern again, but with the rook on h5 this time! However, 17 h3 is problematic for Black.} ({Neil McDonald: 'If he had played the routine'} 16... Rxd6 {Neil McDonald: ', White could play to eliminate the knight on d4 straightaway with'} 17. Be3 {Neil McDonald: 'intending Bxd4, seeing that'} Ne2+ 18. Kh1 {Neil McDonald: 'is nothing for Black.'} Qxa4 19. Nxa4 Ra6 20. Nc5 $10 {Stohl: '='}) 17. Re1 {Neil McDonald: 'was White's reply in the game, cutting out the potential ...Ne2+ move, as the rook could take the knight. Nonetheless Black got a strong attack, mainly because thanks to 16...g5 White was a move slow in challenging the knight with Be3:'} (17. dxc7 $4 {Neil McDonald: '?' Neil McDonald: 'with'} Ne2+ {Neil McDonald: '!'} 18. Kh1 (18. Nxe2 Qxa4 {wins the queen}) 18... Qxh2+ $1 19. Kxh2 Rh6+ $19 {Neil McDonald: 'and mate next move. By playing 16...g5 he cleared the way for the rook to go to h6.'} (19... Rh6+ {King} 20. Qh4 Rxh4#)) (17. Be3 Rxb2 {[%cal Rd4e2] e2-+}) 17... Rxd6 18. Be3 Be5 {King: The most effective move, though King: The most effective move, though Neil McDonald: '!'} (18... Rh6 $5 {King: is also quite good.} 19. Bxd4 (19. h3 Nf3+ 20. gxf3 Qxh3) 19... Bxd4) 19. f4 (19. Bxd4 Qxh2+ 20. Kf1 Bxd4 $19) (19. h3 g4 $1 $40 (19... Nf3+ $2 20. gxf3 Qxh3 21. Qg4 $16) (19... g4 {King} 20. Rad1 gxh3)) 19... gxf4 {King: The advance of the g-pawn proves its worth ...} 20. Bf2 Nf3+ $1 21. gxf3 {Neil McDonald: '- and now we have reached Exercise 3!'} Rg6+ $2 $138 {King: Sadly, this move throws away the win. I imagine time pressure must have been the cause, for the winning move is not difficult.} (21... Qh3 $1 {King: and the rook swings to g6 with decisive effect.} 22. Qe4 (22. Rxe5 Rg6+ 23. Bg3 fxg3 24. hxg3 Qxg3+ 25. Kf1 Qxf3+ 26. Ke1 Qg3+ $19) 22... Bxc3 (22... Rg6+ $2 23. Qxg6+ {[%cal Re1e5] e5}) 23. Qxf4 Bxe1 24. Rxe1 Rfd8 $19) 22. Kf1 Qh3+ 23. Ke2 Bxc3 (23... Re6 $2 24. Ne4 $18) 24. bxc3 Re6+ 25. Kd2 Rd8+ 26. Kc2 {White's  has with Black's help succesfully escaped to safety. Luckily Black still has a perpetual check.} (26. Bd4 $6 c5 $17) 26... Qxf3 (26... Qxh2 $2 27. Qxa7) 27. Bd4 (27. Qxa7 Qd3+ 28. Kb3 Qb5+ $10 {Stohl: '='}) 27... Qg2+ 28. Kb3 Rb8+ 29. Kc4 Rc6+ 30. Kd3 (30. Bc5 $6 Kh8 31. Qxa7 Rd8 {[%cal Rg2d5] d5 is risky for White.}) 30... Qf3+ $10 {Stohl: '=' '='} 31. Kc2 Qg2+ 32. Kd1 Qf3+ 33. Kd2 Qg2+ (33... Qg2+ 34. Kd3 (34. Re2 $4 Rb2+) 34... Qf3+ $10) 1/2-1/2


