1. e4 {Mikhalevski,V Mikhalevski,V Mikhalevski,V Mikhalevski,V: 'Mikhalevski,Victor Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Mikhalevski,V''} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Bc5 {Favourite continuation of A.Miles.Black has been preparing ge7 followed by d5.} 6. Bb5 $146 {This move is already a novelty.White usually preferes 6.e3 or 6.:c6(Kasparov-Leko,Tilburg 1997).See my comments of Van der Wiel-Ernst,1998 in CBM66.} Nge7 ({Now} 6... Qf6 $6 {is not logical as Black gets well-known position without a tempo.} 7. Be3 {In the 4...c5 line white's bishop is still on f1 at the same position.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. Bg5 Bb6 $1 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 9. Re1 (9. Bxc6 $6 dxc6 (9... Bxd4 $2 10. Bxd7 $1 $16 Bxf2+ $140 $2 11. Rxf2 Bxd7 12. Rd2) 10. Nxc6 $6 (10. Na3 $142) 10... bxc6 (10... Qxd1 $4 11. Nxe7+ $18) 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxe7 Re8 $15) (9. Nf5 f6 10. Nxe7+ Nxe7 (10... Qxe7 $5 11. Qd5+ Kh8 12. Bf4 Ne5 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) 11. Bh4 d5 $11) (9. Nxc6 $142 $1 bxc6 (9... dxc6 10. Bc4 $5 $14 {[%mdl 16]} (10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bc4 $14 {[%mdl 16] and White is slightly better in both cases thanks to an extra pawn on the king side.} (11. Bxe7 $2 Re8 12. Bxc6 bxc6 $15 (12... Rxe7 $5 13. Rd1 $1 g6 14. Rd8+ $140 $6 Kg7 15. Re8 $2 Rxe8 16. Bxe8 c6 $1 {[%csl Re8]})))) 10. Bc4 $1 {making d7-d5 difficult.} (10. Bd3 $5) 10... d5 {Black can try to get counterplay at the price of a pawn.} (10... Qe8 $5 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gg6e5]}) 11. exd5 cxd5 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Bxd5 (13. Qxd5 $143 Bg4 $1 14. h3 Rad8 $44) 13... Rb8 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc8a6,Gb8d8,Ge7f6] with some compensation.}) 9... Nxd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. Nc3 (11. exd5 $5 f6 12. Bc4 {[%cal Gd5d6]} Kh8 $1 {[%cal Ge7d5]} (12... Nxd5 $143 13. Nc3 fxg5 (13... c6 14. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1h5,Gd1f3]} (14. Bh4 $5 $14)) 14. Nxd5 Kh8 15. Qd2 $14) 13. Bh4 $5 (13. Bd2 Nxd5 14. Nc3 c6) 13... Nf5 (13... Nxd5 14. Nc3 $14) 14. Bg3 Bxd4 15. Nc3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 $14 {[%csl Re6,Re7] /=}) (11. e5 h6 $1 12. Bh4 (12. Be3 Nf5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8h4]}) (12. Bxe7 Qxe7 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7h4]}) 12... c6 (12... g5 $5 13. Bg3 Nf5 {[%csl Rd4]}) 13. Ba4 g5 14. Bg3 Nf5 {[%csl Rd4]}) 11... f6 12. Be3 Kh8 $5 13. Qd2 $6 (13. exd5 $142 $5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Ba4 $5 {[%cal Ga4b3]}) (13. Bd3) 13... c6 14. Bd3 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%mdl 32] Exchange of white-squared bishops is clearly in the Black's favour.} 16. Bf3 Be6 $1 {[%cal Ge7d5,Gd8d7][%mdl 32]} 17. Na4 $6 (17. Bf4 $142 Bd5 (17... Bf7 18. Rad1 Nd5 19. Bg3 (19. Nxd5 $143 Bxd5 20. Bxd5 Qxd5 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8e8,Gd5a2]})) 18. Bg4 $1 $11) (17. d5 $6 Bxd5 $1 (17... cxd5 $4 18. Bxb6 Qxb6 19. Qe2 $18) (17... Nxd5 $4 18. Bxb6 $18 {[%cal Ge1e6]})) 17... Bd5 $1 {[%mdl 32] The prolongation of the same strategy.} 18. Bg4 Ng6 $1 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Re3][%cal Gf6f5,Gf5f4] By the series of strong moves Black takes initiative in his hands.} 19. Nc5 $4 {[%mdl 8192] After this careless move White loses by force.} (19. Nc3 {was necessary with chances to equalize.}) 19... f5 $19 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 20. Bg5 (20. Bh5 f4 21. Bxg6 fxe3 22. Qxe3 hxg6 $19) 20... Ba5 $1 {[%mdl 64] Perhaps White missed this strong intermediate move.Now all is over.} (20... Ba5 $1 21. b4 (21. Qe3 f4 $1 22. Bxd8 fxe3 {[%cal Ge3f2]} 23. Rxe3 Bxd8 $19) (21. Qc1 Qc7 $19 {winning an exchange.} 22. Bf3 $140 Bxe1) 21... Bxb4 $1 22. Qxb4 Qxg5 23. Bh3 Nf4 $19) 0-1


