1. e4 {Schlosser,P King} c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Ng3 e6 $5 7. Be2 $6 $146 (7. Bd3) (7. Bc4) (7. c3) 7... c5 8. O-O cxd4 $1 (8... Qc7 9. c4 cxd4 {[%cal Rd4e2] e2-+} 10. Qxd4 (10. Nxd4 a6 11. a3 Ne5 12. Be3 Bd7) 10... b6 11. Bf4 Qc5 12. Qc3 (12. Rfd1) 12... Bb7 13. Rad1 Be7 $10 14. Nd4 $5 (14. Ng5 $32 $15 O-O $6 15. Qc2 {[%cal Rc6d4] d4} Rfd8 16. b4 Qc6 17. Bf3 Qc8 18. Bd6 Bxd6 19. Rxd6 $15 Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Qc7 21. Rfd1 $36) 14... e5 15. Nb3 Qc7 16. Be3 O-O 17. Nf5 $132 Rfe8) 9. Nxd4 (9. Qxd4 $5 {King: is also quite good.} Be7 (9... Bc5) 10. Bf4 O-O 11. c4 b6 12. Ne4 Bb7 $4 13. Nc3 Nc5 (13... Rc8 $1 14. Rad1 Nc5 $19 15. Nb5 {King})) 9... Bc5 10. b3 O-O $1 11. Bb2 a6 (11... Qc7 12. Qd2 b6 (12... a6) 13. Nb5 Qb8 14. Rad1 Bb7 $19 15. c4 a6 16. Nd6 Bc6 $19 17. Nh5 Qc7 $1 $40 (17... Nxh5) 18. Nxg7 $2 Kxg7 19. Qg5+ Kh8 $16 20. Ne8 {King}) 12. c4 Qc7 13. a3 $6 {ףa4 White's strongest piece will be misplaced here.} (13. Bf3 Ne5) 13... b6 14. b4 (14. Bf3 Bb7 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 $19 16. Qf3 $2 Qxf3 {[%cal Re1e5] e5} 17. Nxf3) 14... Be7 $36 15. Re1 Bb7 16. Bd3 {King: Black could simply play 16...Rxd6 here, and it is hard to believe that he stands worse with such active pieces, even if White captured on a7. But Ashley's attention must have been drawn to the tempting 16...Ne2+ 17 Kh1 Rb4, hoping for 18 Qxa7? Qxh2+ 19 Kxh2 Rh4 mate. Unfortunately White more than saves the day with 18 Qd7, preventing the sacrifice, and leaving Black in trouble. Nevertheless, this motif must have sparked off a new line of thought, and after forty minutes Black played} Rfe8 $1 {King: After this, Black's position just clicks. The main point of the move is seen in the following variation: 17 dxc7 Ne2+ 18 Kh1 Qxh2+ 19 Kxh2 Rh6+. A pleasing echo of the variation above. The advance of the g-pawn allows the rook to swing over to h6, and at the same time blocks the path of the bishop from c1; moreover, it can be used to force open lines if White plays h3.  Incidentally, I showed this position to Bob Wade (without revealing 16...g5) and he came up with another idea: 16...Rb5!?, threatening Ne2+ and Qxh2+; the same mating pattern again, but with the rook on h5 this time! However, 17 h3 is problematic for Black.} 17. Qe2 (17. Nh5) (17. Rc1) 17... Nf8 18. Rac1 Ng6 {King: The most effective move, though} 19. Qc2 Nf4 {King: The advance of the g-pawn proves its worth ...} 20. Bf1 Rad8 $1 21. c5 (21. Nde2 $6 Nd3 $17) (21. Nge2 $2 Be4 $18) (21. Rcd1 $1 {King: and the rook swings to g6 with decisive effect.}) 21... bxc5 $2 $138 {King: Sadly, this move throws away the win. I imagine time pressure must have been the cause, for the winning move is not difficult.} 22. bxc5 Bd5 23. Nde2 Rc8 24. Nxf4 Qxf4 25. Bxa6 Rxc5 26. Qe2 {White's  has with Black's help succesfully escaped to safety. Luckily Black still has a perpetual check.} Ra8 27. Bb5 (27. Bd3) 27... Ng4 28. a4 Rac8 29. Qf1 h5 30. f3 Nxh2 $10 31. Ne2 Qd2 32. Kxh2 Qxb2 33. Rxc5 Rxc5 34. Kh1 Bd6 35. Ng1 $10 Qd4 $4 36. Nh3 Rc2 $6 37. Rd1 Qe5 38. f4 {[%cal Rg2d5] d5 is risky for White.} Qe3 39. Rxd5 exd5 40. a5 $10 Rc1 $2 1/2-1/2


