1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Qf3 Qb6 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Rhe1 h6 {Moves like these in a very charged positions can be truly dangerous, since instead of developing extra piece black is simply throwing more oil into the fire.} 12. e5 Bb7 13. Qh3 dxe5 (13... Nxe5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. f4 (16. Qxe6 Qxf2 $1 $17) 16... Nc4 17. Qxe6 Qc7 18. Bxc4 bxc4 19. Rxd6 $40) 14. Nxe6 fxe6 (14... Rh7 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. f4 e4 17. Nd4 $36) 15. Bxe6 Rd8 (15... Nf8 16. Rxe5 Rd8 17. Rde1 $16) 16. Rxd7 $1 Rxd7 (16... Nxd7 17. Qh5+ g6 18. Qxg6+ Kf8 19. Qf7#) (16... Qxf2 17. Bxf6 $3 (17. Rxd8+ $6 Kxd8 18. Rd1+ Kc7 19. Bh4 Qf4+ 20. Kb1 Rd8 $11) 17... Qxe1+ (17... Qxf6 18. Rxb7 $18) 18. Nd1 Rxd7 (18... Qe4 19. Rxe7+ Kf8 20. Rf7+ Ke8 21. Bxd8 $18) 19. Bxd7+ Kd8 20. Bxe7+ Kc7 (20... Kxe7 21. Qe6+ Kd8 22. Qd6 $18) 21. Qe6 $18) 17. Bxf6 Rd6 $2 {It is easy to understand Nakamura's wish to save his extra exchange, but this move loses. In comparison 17...xf6 seems good enough for the full equality.} (17... Bxf6 18. Bxd7+ Ke7 $1 19. Rd1 (19. f3 Rd8 20. Rd1 Bg5+ 21. Kb1 b4 22. Ne4 Bc8 $17) (19. Bc8 Bxc8 20. Nd5+ Kd6 21. Qxc8 Rxc8 22. Nxb6 Rd8 23. c4 Bg5+ 24. Kc2 Kc6 25. Nd5 bxc4 $15) 19... Rd8 20. Kb1 Qxf2 21. Qe6+ Kf8 22. Qd6+ Be7 23. Qxe5 Bxg2 $11) 18. Qh5+ Kd8 19. Bxe7+ Kxe7 20. Qxe5 Kd8 21. Nd5 $6 (21. Bd5 $1 Bxd5 (21... Rf6 22. Qe7+ Kc8 23. Qxg7 Rhf8 24. Re7 Bc6 25. Ne4 Bxd5 26. Nxf6 Qxf6 27. Re8+ Rxe8 28. Qxf6 $18) 22. Nxd5 Qc5 23. Qxg7 $18) 21... Bxd5 22. Bxd5 Qc7 (22... Rd7 23. Bf3 Qc7 24. Qe4 $16) 23. f4 Rd7 24. Qf5 (24. Qe4 Qd6 25. c4 bxc4 26. Bxc4 Rf8 27. g3 $14) 24... Qc5 25. Be6 $2 {[%mdl 8192] Ashley has lost control of the game few moves ago, but this natural retreat is a real losing blunder.} (25. Rd1 Rf8 26. Qe4 Rf6 27. f5 Rfd6 28. b4 Qc3 29. Rd3 Qa1+ 30. Kd2 Qb2 $11) 25... Qf2 $1 (25... Qf2 $1 26. Qe4 Qd2+ 27. Kb1 Qd1+ 28. Rxd1 Rxd1#) 0-1


